  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Arranging Housing Before Arrival</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The Netherlands, especially Amsterdam, has a severe housing crisis. You must register at the municipality within 5 days of arrival—impossible without an address. Start searching months in advance, use university housing if available, consider smaller cities.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Missing the 5-Day Registration Deadline</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">You must register at the gemeente (municipality) within 5 days of arrival to get your BSN. Without a BSN, you can't open a bank account, start work, or access many services. Make this appointment immediately upon arrival.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Understanding the Working/Insurance Rule</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">If you work 32+ hours/month, you MUST switch to Dutch basic insurance (basisverzekering). This is law, not optional. Getting caught without proper insurance while working can result in fines and problems with your residence permit.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Forgetting Dental Isn't Covered</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Dutch basic insurance does NOT cover dental for adults. A filling can cost €100-200 out of pocket. Either get supplementary dental insurance, do dental work before coming, or budget for out-of-pocket dental costs.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Getting a Work Permit When Needed</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Non-EU students need a work permit (TWV) to work, even part-time. Your employer must apply for this—it's not automatic. Make sure any job you take has a valid TWV in place before you start working.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in the Netherlands -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in the Netherlands</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The Dutch healthcare system is efficient and high-quality, but works differently than many countries. The key concept: the huisarts (GP) is your gatekeeper to all other care. You can't just walk into a specialist—you need a GP referral first.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How Dutch Healthcare Works</h3>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-green-200 bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">What's Covered</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>✓ GP visits (after eigen risico)</li>
          <li>✓ Specialist care (with referral)</li>
          <li>✓ Hospital treatment</li>
          <li>✓ Prescription medications</li>
          <li>✓ Mental healthcare (with referral)</li>
          <li>✓ Maternity care</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-red-200 bg-red-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-red-900 mb-3">NOT Covered (Adults)</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-red-800">
          <li>✗ Dental care (children only)</li>
          <li>✗ Physiotherapy (first 20 sessions)</li>
          <li>✗ Glasses/contacts (children only)</li>
          <li>✗ Alternative medicine</li>
          <li>✗ Cosmetic procedures</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">The Eigen Risico (Deductible)</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Dutch basic insurance has a mandatory deductible called <strong>eigen risico</strong>—€385/year (2024). You pay the first €385 of covered care each year before insurance pays. Some exceptions:
    </p>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 mb-6">
      <li><strong>GP visits:</strong> Exempt from deductible (free after insurance)</li>
      <li><strong>Maternity care:</strong> Exempt from deductible</li>
      <li><strong>Specialist care:</strong> Counts toward deductible</li>
      <li><strong>Hospital stays:</strong> Count toward deductible</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How to Access Healthcare</h3>

    <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Step 1: Register with a Huisarts</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Find a GP (huisarts) near your home and register. This is essential—you need a huisarts to access any specialist care. Use zorgkaartnederland.nl to find one accepting new patients.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Step 2: Book Through Your Huisarts</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">For any health issue, start with your huisarts. They'll either treat you, refer you to a specialist, or advise self-care. Don't skip this step—specialists won't see you without a referral.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Step 3: Huisartsenpost for Urgent Care</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">For urgent issues outside GP hours (evenings, weekends), call your local huisartsenpost (GP post). They provide after-hours care. For emergencies, call 112.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Emergencies</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Call 112 for life-threatening emergencies. Go to hospital spoedeisende hulp (emergency room) for serious injuries. For non-urgent issues outside GP hours, call huisartsenpost first.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4 mt-6">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>University health services:</strong> Most Dutch universities have student health services offering free basic care, mental health support, and guidance. Use these—they're often faster than finding a huisarts and understand student-specific issues.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need Dutch basic insurance or can I use student insurance?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          It depends on whether you work. If you don't work (or work fewer than 32 hours/month), student insurance (AON, OOM) is fine and cheaper (~€60/month). If you work 32+ hours/month, you MUST join Dutch basic insurance (€130+/month)—it's the law.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is the zoekjaar (orientation year)?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          After graduating from a Dutch university, you can apply for the zoekjaar—a 1-year residence permit to find work. You can work any job during this time, and once employed, switch to a regular work permit. Apply within 3 years of graduation.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is dental covered by Dutch insurance?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No—dental care is NOT covered by Dutch basic insurance for adults (only children under 18). Student insurance often includes basic dental. If on Dutch basic, add aanvullende verzekering (supplementary insurance) with dental coverage, or budget for out-of-pocket costs.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is the eigen risico (deductible)?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Dutch basic insurance has a €385/year mandatory deductible (eigen risico). You pay the first €385 of covered care before insurance kicks in. GP visits and maternity care are exempt. Student insurance often has lower or no deductible.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I work while studying in the Netherlands?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes, but with conditions. Non-EU students need a work permit (TWV)—your employer must apply for this. You can work up to 16 hours/week during the academic year or full-time in summer (June-August). EU students have no restrictions.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How hard is it to find housing?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Very hard, especially in Amsterdam. The Netherlands has a housing crisis. Start searching 3-6 months before arrival. Use university housing if available. Consider smaller cities (Groningen, Eindhoven, Maastricht) where housing is easier. Budget €400-1,000/month depending on location.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The Netherlands offers one of the easiest paths for international students: your university handles the visa process, most programs are in English, and the zoekjaar gives you time to find work after graduation. The trade-off is higher costs than Germany or France and a challenging housing market.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Health insurance is straightforward if you understand the work rule: student insurance (~€60/month) if not working, Dutch basic (€130+/month) if working 32+ hours/month. Just remember dental isn't covered for adults—plan accordingly.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      For students who want an English-speaking environment, central European location, and strong post-study work prospects, the Netherlands is an excellent choice. Start housing search early, arrange insurance before arrival, and you'll be set for a great experience.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Bottom Line</h3>
      <p class="text-primary-800 mb-4">
        The Netherlands offers a smooth visa process (university handles it), English-taught programs, and a 1-year job search visa after graduation. Health insurance depends on work status—student insurance for non-workers, Dutch basic if working 32+ hours/month. Dental isn't covered—budget separately. Housing is the biggest challenge—start early.
      </p>
